outlooksByWeek.2: Even though he netted more touches than Alexander Mattison against the Bengals, Abdullah still isn't relevant in fantasy terms heading into Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Sent one target on his only route last week, Abdullah isn't a real factor in real or fantasy terms heading into this big conference matchup.
outlooksByWeek.4: Dalvin Cook's absence elevated Abdullah to No. 2 on the Vikings running back depth chart. Even so, Alexander Mattison saw the lion's share of action, leaving just five carries for Abdullah. Even if Cook is unable to suit up in Week 4, Abdullah isn't in the fantasy mix.
outlooksByWeek.5: In the Vikings' Week 4 loss to the Browns, Abdullah caught his lone target, turning it into a one-yard catch. He played on only five offensive snaps, however, and should not be in fantasy lineups for Minnesota's Week 5 game against Detroit.

outlooksByWeek.1: Last season, Adams was on pace for one of, if not the best season from a wide receiver in history, but he missed two games. No wideout in the league is blessed with Adams’ combination of high floor and unlimited ceiling. With Aaron Rodgers back at helm, expect Adams to be the top-ranked wideout almost every week, which is where he sits Week 1 against the New Orleans Saints in what should be a high-scoring affair.
outlooksByWeek.2: The Packers' offense simply couldn't get untracked against the Saints, resulting in a quiet line from Adams. A loud line could be on the way, though, as Adams should get back to a heavy workload against a Detroit defense that allowed a series of splash plays in the air last week.
outlooksByWeek.3: A rare blend of efficiency and volume fuels Adams' undeniable fantasy success. The Packers fed Adams with nine targets in a run-heavy Week 2 showing, while another big workload is on the way in a key conference showdown with San Francisco.
outlooksByWeek.4: Another elite prime-time performance from Adams saw him deliver his 25th career 100-yard receiving game, tying him for third-most in Packers history with Jordy Nelson. Pittsburgh is up next and has allowed the second-most yards to receivers among AFC secondaries, suggesting Adams could still eat against an otherwise solid defense.
outlooksByWeek.5: Adams caught 6-of-11 targets for 64 yards in the Packers' Week 4 win over the Steelers. It wasn't Adams' best day and his troubles were compounded by Randall Cobb emerging to catch a pair of touchdowns from Aaron Rodgers. Nonetheless, Adams drew a 30.5% target share in this game and he's averaging 11.5 targets through the first four contests. There is no universe in which Adams isn't a fantasy WR1 going up against the Bengals in Week 5.

player.seasonOutlook: Adams was the top-scoring fantasy WR of 2020 by 29 points, which is incredible, considering he missed 2.5 games due to injury. Including a pair of playoff games, Adams was targeted at least nine times in 14 of his 15 full games and posted a ridiculous 130-1,471-20 receiving line during that span. He reached double-digit TDs for the fourth time in five seasons and posted a top-10 fantasy week in a position-best 57% of his regular-season outings. Adams averaged a career-high (and league-high) 34% target share, and he's now been at or above 30% each of the past three seasons. The 28-year-old hasn't appeared in 16 games in a regular season since 2016, but he's so good when active that we can deal with some missed time. Aaron Rodgers' top weapon is the best WR in fantasy.

outlooksByWeek.1: Coming off of a strong 2020 season for the Raiders, Agholor opens his tenure in New England as a starter with big-play potential. However, a Week 1 matchup against a tough Miami secondary will not be the best opportunity for fantasy managers to see if their late-round investment in him pays off.
outlooksByWeek.2: Agholor will likely be a popular free agent this week after compiled 72 yards on five receptions, including a touchdown. While his Week 1 performance was encouraging, it could be a different story when defenses scheme against the veteran wideout. Temper expectations while considering Agholor as a deep league flex option against the Jets secondary in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Despite notching 50 of 58 offensive snaps, Agholor collected only three targets, securing them all for 21 yards as his Week 2 production dipped considerably from the Patriots opener. Agholor will be involved every week, but in Josh McDaniels' offense, he can’t be trusted enough to be a fantasy factor, especially in Week 3 matched up with the Saints secondary.
outlooksByWeek.4: Averaging just 5.7 targets per game and able to catch just two of his seven targets this last week, Agholor's debut season in New England is off to a slow start. The Buccaneers have some injuries in the secondary, although it's unclear if Agholor can exploit them.
outlooksByWeek.5: Agholor’s downfield skills were utilized in Week 4 as he grabbed three passes for 55 yards in New England’s 19-17 loss to Tampa in Foxboro. While it’s clear Agholor will have his number called a handful of times each game, he’s not reliable enough to be deployed for fantasy purposes.

player.seasonOutlook: Agholor signed with the Patriots after enjoying a bit of a resurgence during his lone season with the Raiders. Following an up-and-down five years in Philadelphia, Agholor put together a strong 48-896-8 receiving line on 81 targets last season. He struggled with drops (seven) but was heavily targeted down field (15.4 aDOT was third highest among WRs) and answered the bell with plenty of explosive plays (his 18.7 YPR ranked second and his 11.1 YPT fourth). Agholor is entering his seventh NFL season at age 28 and has yet to post a top-20 fantasy campaign (he has finished better than 34th once: 2017). Agholor very well could lead New England in targets, but consistent flex production may be a lot to ask in a run-heavy scheme that will throw to its RBs and TEs often. Agholor is a fine bench option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Agnew's familiarity with Jacksonville OC Darrell Bevell's scheme from their time together in Detroit won't be enough to make the receiver fantasy relevant in 2021.
outlooksByWeek.2: Agnew did not receive any targets in Week 1. His role in the Jaguars offense is too small for him to matter much in fantasy.
outlooksByWeek.3: Agnew did not receive any targets in Week 2. The No. 5 WR option for a weak Jacksonville offense doesn't hold any fantasy appeal.
outlooksByWeek.4: Agnew now has one of the longest possible plays in NFL history after returning Matt Prater's missed 68-yard field goal attempt for a 109-yard touchdown in Jacksonville's Week 3 loss to the Cardinals. Still, despite the big-play ability, Agnew should not be in fantasy lineups against the Bengals in Week 4.
outlooksByWeek.5: Agnew’s involvement may pick up a little now that DJ Chark has been ruled out for the season, but it won’t approach fantasy type prediction. Agnew’s chief responsibility remains as one of the top punt returners in the league.

outlooksByWeek.1: Ahmed fared well in the lead role for Miami when Myles Gaskin missed time last season, but he was a non-factor when Gaskins was healthy. This week, Gaskins is healthy, so Ahmed will likely be a non-factor against New England.
outlooksByWeek.2: Ahmed appears ticketed to be Miami’s No. 3 running back, getting most of his snaps in passing downs. Since the Dolphins offense should rank near the bottom in total plays, Ahmed’s production does not register as fantasy worthy.
outlooksByWeek.3: Netting 4.1 yards per touch in a limited complementary role, Ahmed might not even be the second-most valuable fantasy back on the roster ahead of this game against the Raiders.
outlooksByWeek.4: Despite Miami's commitment to running the ball and short passes, Ahmed only saw five offensive snaps in Week 3, failing to register a touch. This lack of involvement is not conducive to fantasy production.
outlooksByWeek.5: Ahmed handled the ball on each of his five offensive snaps in Week 4, gaining one yard on three carries while catching two passes for 12 yards. The efficiency is nice, but the volume remains well below fantasy level.

player.seasonOutlook: Ahmed went undrafted last year, but the former Washington Husky leapt onto the fantasy radar when Myles Gaskin went down with an injury last season. In the three games in which he played at least 60% of the snaps, Ahmed totaled 291 yards and two TDs on 63 touches. He was fantasy's No. 7 RB those weeks. Ahmed was reduced to a complementary role once Gaskin returned and will compete with newcomer Malcolm Brown for No. 2 duties in 2021. The 22-year-old is no more than an insurance option and doesn't need to be drafted.

outlooksByWeek.1: It will be interesting to see if a preseason hamstring hampers Aiyuk at all in the opener against Detroit. If he's all good, this second-year breakout candidate could thrive against a Lions secondary that allowed the third-most fantasy points to receivers last season.
outlooksByWeek.2: Aiyuk was active for the 49ers opener, but a lingering hamstring injury limited him to just 26 snaps and no targets. He enters Week 2 as questionable for San Francisco’s visit to Philadelphia for their matchup with the Eagles. Even if he plays, Aiyuk is too risky to trust until he proves fully healthy and is integrated back into the 49ers offense.
outlooksByWeek.3: A frustrating start to the season has included inconsistent snap counts and a lack of overall attention from his quarterback. It's nearly impossible to start Aiyuk with confidence at this stage, instead hoping that he earns a more significant role against the Packers this week.
outlooksByWeek.4: Back to running a full set of routes opposite Deebo Samuel, Aiyuk finally enjoyed a solid showing thanks to six targets and some red zone attention. The Seahawks don't claim a great set of outside corners, although there is still some downside to consider in this low-volume passing game.
outlooksByWeek.5: Trailing Deebo Samuel by 11 routes and 17 snaps this past week, Aiyuk remains in an unideal spot for fantasy success. Until we see him reestablish his place as a top target in this somewhat low-volume passing game, the second-year receiver isn't a fantasy starter for this division matchup with the Cardinals.

player.seasonOutlook: The 2020 49ers' offense was so overwhelmed with injuries that Aiyuk - a rookie - missed four games and still finished first among the team's non-linemen in offensive snaps. Seriously. Aiyuk posted a 60-748-5 receiving line and added 77 yards and two TDs on six carries during 12 active weeks, which was enough for the ninth-most fantasy points among WRs during that span. Aiyuk, who averaged 12.6 targets per game during a five-game stretch late in the season, may see a dip in usage with Deebo Samuel and George Kittle (among others) now healthy, but the 2020 first-round pick certainly looked the part as a rookie. Consider him a WR3 with upside.
Cam Akers is expected to miss the entire 2021 season after rupturing his Achilles.

outlooksByWeek.1: With multiple players capable of contributing to the TE position for the Texans, Akins shouldn't be in your fantasy lineup against the Jaguars this week.
outlooksByWeek.2: Akins was held catchless on two targets in Week 1 against Jacksonville. While he will have a small role in Houston's offense going forward, Akins should not be in your fantasy lineup.
outlooksByWeek.3: Akins turned two targets into one catch for 17 yards against the Browns in Week 2. He should not be in fantasy lineups against the Panthers in Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: Akins pulled in 4-of-5 targets for 32 yards in the Texans' Week 3 loss to the Panthers. It was a strong showing for a player with just one catch for 17 yards through the first two games, but Akins should not be in fantasy lineups in Week 4 against the Bills.
outlooksByWeek.5: Akins caught his only target for four yards in Week 4. While Akins may get more looks in Week 5’s home encounter with New England, he’s not in play for fantasy purposes.

player.seasonOutlook: Akins emerged as the top fantasy TE in Houston last season, though that's not saying much, as the 2018 third-round pick was held to his second consecutive TE25 fantasy campaign. Akins posted a 36-418-2 receiving line in 2019 before landing on a 37-403-1 line (in 13 games) last season. The 29-year-old is entering a key contract year, but it seems likely that he's already at or near his fantasy ceiling. That's especially the case with Deshaun Watson's future in doubt and with 2019 third-round pick Kahale Warring in the mix for a larger role. Akins doesn't need to be drafted.

outlooksByWeek.1: Alie-Cox and Jack Doyle more or less split TE targets for a run-leaning offense in 2020, and there's unlikely to be enough work to make either relevant in Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Alie-Cox drew only two targets in Week 1 against the Seahawks, but he failed to catch either of them. His limited role in the Colts offense should keep him out of your fantasy lineup in Week 2 against the Rams.
outlooksByWeek.3: Alie-Cox finished the Week 2 loss to the Rams with one catch for 18 yards on two targets. He was out-snapped and out-produced by Jack Doyle. Alie-Cox should not be in starting lineups against the Titans in Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: Alie-Cox caught both his looks for 14 yards in Week 3. He'll continue to see the odd target now and again, but as the No. 2 tight end on a team favoring the 11 personnel set, Alie-Cox isn't even a blip on the fantasy radar.
outlooksByWeek.5: Two scores this past week hides the fact the team still employs a busy committee at tight end that often limits consistency. The Ravens are solid in coverage, thus Alie-Cox can be left in free agency.

player.seasonOutlook: Alie-Cox was on the field for a career-high 45% of the offensive snaps last season, but couldn't emerge as a legitimate fantasy option in the merry-go-round that was the Colts' tight end room. Alie-Cox posted a 31-394-2 receiving line in 16 games, though 8-161-1 of that came in two early-season games. Alie-Cox's efficiency was good, as the 2017 UDFA ranked no lower than sixth in catch rate, YPT and RAC. In seven seasons, coach Frank Reich has never had a TE unit fall below a 23% target share (27% average), but that was the case in 2020 when Alie-Cox only handled 7% of the targets. The 27-year-old will compete with Jack Doyle and rookie Kylen Granson for snaps this season and is a longshot to join the TE1 discussion.

outlooksByWeek.1: Allen might need his legs against a Steelers defense that led the league in sacks and allowed the fewest fantasy points to passers last season. It helps then that no quarterback has more rushing touchdowns than Allen since the start of the 2018 season. In fact, he's ninth in the entire league in rushing scores since being drafted.
outlooksByWeek.2: Allen’s arm and legs were on display in the Week 1 opener, but he mustered only one passing touchdown in the Bills 23-16 home loss to the Pittsburgh Steelers. Don’t fret, Allen will produce bountiful scores through the air and on the ground. In fact, he is not only the top QB on the board, Allen projects for the most fantasy points among all positions in Week 2 as the Bills visit the Miami Dolphins.
outlooksByWeek.3: The Bills put 35 points on the NFL scoreboard, but Allen looked off once again in Week 2, passing for just 179 yards and a pair of scores. He faces a strong Washington defense this week, but a rebound is inevitable.  He's one of the best overall QB options in Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: He's back! After less-than-robust performances over the first two weeks, Allen hit on all cylinders in the Bills' Week 3 win over Washington. The third-year signal caller completed 32-of-43 passes for 358 yards and four touchdowns (without an interception) while adding nine yards and a touchdown on four carries. Allen is a locked in QB1 on a weekly basis. He's among the top plays overall in Week 4 against the Texans.
outlooksByWeek.5: His first dropback was an interception in Week 4, but the rest was pretty awesome, as Allen tallied nearly 300 total yards with two scores in a drubbing of the Texans. Next up is a marquee matchup with the Chiefs in a game with an awesome point total.

player.seasonOutlook: Allen was last season's top scoring fantasy QB thanks to a breakout in his third pro campaign. The 25-year-old ranked no lower than sixth among QBs in pass attempts, completions, passing yards, passing TDs, completion percentage and YPA. He also continued to deliver the goods with his legs, scoring at least eight rushing TDs for the third consecutive season. Buffalo operated the league's second pass-heaviest offense in 2020 and that philosophy doesn't figure to change much as long as Allen is under center. The 25-year-old has cemented himself as an elite fantasy QB.

outlooksByWeek.1: Allen made 100 receptions for 992 yards in 2020 and was one of the NFL's top target-getters after Justin Herbert took over QB duties for the Chargers last year. Still the Week 1 matchup against a strong Washington defense is difficult, though not enough to lower Allen beyond the WR1/WR2 range.
outlooksByWeek.2: The team's resident target magnet pulled a cool 13 looks in Week 1 and delivered a clean 100 yards. Looking ahead, Allen's investors can smile realizing how the Cowboys gave up gobs of yards to the Buccaneers' receivers last week.
outlooksByWeek.3: Allen turned eight targets into four catches for 108 yards against the Cowboys in Week 2. With a pair of 100-yard receiving outings now under his belt, Allen heads into the Week 3 game against the Chiefs as a rock-solid WR1 for your fantasy team.
outlooksByWeek.4: This reception machine is fueled by an amazingly consistent stream of targets. Allen regularly earns double-digit looks from Justin Herbert. There are some inviting metrics to consider for this division matchup, as the Raiders are allowing 20.3 receptions to receivers per game on the year, third-most in the league.
outlooksByWeek.5: This target magnet wasn't able to get untracked against the Raiders this past week, but the workload remained impressive. Cleveland has been really good against receivers early this season, but Allen is also a really good receiver.

player.seasonOutlook: Another season, another strong campaign from Allen. The 2013 third-round pick missed two games but finished top-13 in targets, receptions, receiving yards and fantasy points for the fourth season in a row. Allen has settled in as a short-area target, posting a career-low 9.9 YPR in 2020, but he also averaged 10.5 targets per game (his highest since 2015) and matched a career-high with eight TDs last season. Now 29 years old, Allen's play could see a dip in the near future, but he remains the clear No. 1 target in an ascending Justin Herbert-led offense. Consider Allen a fringe WR1.

outlooksByWeek.2: Amendola finished the Week 1 win over the Jaguars with five catches (on five targets) for 35 yards and a touchdown. Despite the scoring play and a relatively robust workload, fantasy managers should wait for more clarity on his week-to-week role before inserting him in lineups.
outlooksByWeek.3: Amendola caught his lone target to finish with nine yards from scrimmage in the Week 2 loss in Cleveland. Amendola, who came out of the game with a hamstring issue, should not be in fantasy lineups against Carolina in Week 3.

outlooksByWeek.1: In 2020, Anderson posted the first 1,000-yard season of his NFL career and quietly finished as a top-20 fantasy option. Now reunited with former Jets teammate Sam Darnold, Anderson is poised to take another step forward in 2021. View him as a solid WR2 this week.
outlooksByWeek.2: Anderson had a single reception on his three Week 1 targets, but it did go for 57 yards and a score. The lack of targets is a bit concerning in a now-crowded Carolina offense.  Still, Anderson firmly projects as a WR3 this week.
outlooksByWeek.3: Anderson turned six targets into three catches for 38 yards against the Saints in Week 2. That he doubled up his target total from Week 1 is promising. That he faces a generous Texans defense in Week 3 keeps him firmly in WR3 territory.
outlooksByWeek.4: Anderson's quiet season got even quieter in Week 3 as he caught only one pass for eight yards. Week 4 brings a favorable matchup in Dallas, However, while the club has expressed the need to get him the ball more often, until he and Sam Darnold display more chemistry, Anderson is best used as a flex in very deep leagues.
outlooksByWeek.5: Anderson garnered 11 targets in Week 4, matching the combined total from the first three games. The volume is encouraging, but he only caught five for 46 yards as Sam Darnold and DJ Moore have developed early season chemistry. Anderson’s secondary role drops him to a flex option in deep leagues in Week 5 when Philadelphia visits Carolina.

player.seasonOutlook: Anderson is entering his second season with the Panthers after a successful 2020 campaign in which he handled a career-high 8.5 targets per game (26% share) and finished as fantasy's No. 19-scoring WR. Anderson's role was much different than it was with the Jets, as he was used less as a vertical weapon (9.4 aDOT compared to 14.8 with Jets), which led to career-high showings in targets, receptions and receiving yards. The only problem area for Anderson was scoring TDs, as he found pay dirt only three times (his fewest since 2016). The 28-year-old is ticketed for a similar role in 2021 and very well could benefit from Sam Darnold's arrival, Curtis Samuel's departure and some regression to the mean in the TD department. Anderson is a fine WR3 target.

outlooksByWeek.3: Anderson was targeted twice, catching both passes for nine yards, in a Week 2 loss to the Cowboys. The two targets give him four over the first two games. He should not be in fantasy lineups against the Chiefs in Week 3.

outlooksByWeek.1: Andrews again checks in as one of the top tight ends in the league, though there is a big drop from Travis Kelce and Darren Weller to the next tier. Still, Andrews is routinely a key cog in the Ravens passing game and is usually busy in the red zone. Look for Andrews to get off to a solid start as the Raiders allowed the most fantasy points to tight ends last season.
outlooksByWeek.2: A quiet opener saw Andrews busy blocking at times, with just five targets and roughly 40 air yards sent his way. The hope is that a marquee matchup expected to prove high-scoring against the Chiefs will garner this gifted tight end a bigger share of the offense in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: It’s been only two games, but Andrews has yet to see a red zone target after being one of Lamar Jackson’s most trusted receivers near the goal line over the past two seasons. Even so, Andrews remains one of the top tight ends with Jackson still using him to move the chains. Andrews lines up for another TE1 worthy week, facing a Lions defense giving up the 11th most points per game to the position so far this season.
outlooksByWeek.4: Each week of the season has included Andrews increasing his target share of the Baltimore passing game. This past week, he consumed a season-high 26 percent of the targets and delivered a big game. The Broncos have been stingy on defense in allowing the eighth-fewest fantasy points to tight ends, although Andrews' workload could help offset matchup concerns.
outlooksByWeek.5: Pacing the Ravens with seven targets in Week 4, Andrews also ran the most routes on the team en route to his third straight game with as many as five catches. Andrews is positioned to meet his projection against a Colts defense that has allowed nearly 12 fantasy points per game to tight ends.

player.seasonOutlook: Andrews is heading into his fourth NFL season having posted back-to-back top-six fantasy campaigns. The 2018 third-round pick has never finished a season better than 19th at the position in pass routes, but benefits from a huge target share (25% in both 2019 and 2020), his role as a vertical target (Top 5 in aDOT each of the past three seasons) and tons goal line work (his 17 TDs are tied for first, his 15.1 OTD ranks second and his 23 end zone targets ranks first among TEs over the past two seasons). In 2020, Andrews missed a pair of games, but still tied for third with eight top-10 fantasy weeks. The 26-year-old is one of Lamar Jackson's top targets and locked in as a top-five fantasy TE.

outlooksByWeek.2: Arcega-Whiteside hurt his ankle in the fourth quarter of the Eagles season-opening trouncing of the Falcons. Even if he’s able to suit up for the club’s Week 2 home opener with the 49ers, Arcega-Whiteside is well off the fantasy radar.

outlooksByWeek.1: Reports out of Carolina in recent weeks have suggested that new QB Sam Darnold has targeted Arnold heavily in practices this summer. Still, as he's projected for less than five fantasy points, Arnold isn't a recommended play against the Jets in Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Arnold had a pair of catches on his three targets for  a meager six yards in Week 1. Arnold and Ian Thomas split the scraps left behind by Christian McCaffrey and Carolina's prolific WR trio. As such, neither player makes for a good TE option in this offense.
outlooksByWeek.3: Arnold caught 3-of-4 targets for 55 yards against the Saints in Week 2. While he's getting more targets and has more catches than fellow TE Ian Thomas, even the mere presence of Thomas dilutes Arnold's opportunities. Arnold should not be in starting lineups against the Texans in Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: Acquired in a trade with the Panthers on Monday, Arnold immediately moves ahead of Jacob Hollister as the team's top fantasy prospect at tight end with James O'Shaughnessy on IR. That said, Arnold should not be in starting lineups for his Jaguars debut against the Bengals in Week 4.
outlooksByWeek.5: Arnold caught a pair of balls for 17 yards in Jacksonville’s Week 4 Thursday night loss to Cincinnati. Arnold was on the field for 17 snaps just three days after being acquired from the Panthers. Even with extra time to learn his new team’s offense, Arnold isn’t a fantasy candidate in Week 5.

player.seasonOutlook: Arnold signed with Carolina after spending the past two seasons in Arizona. Arnold entered the NFL as an undrafted WR back in 2017, but successfully made the transition to tight end over the past few years. After totaling 20 catches in his first two NFL seasons, Arnold played 41% of Arizona's snaps and posted a solid 31-438-4 receiving line in 2020. Arnold's 12.5 aDOT was tops among TEs and his efficiency was terrific, as he caught 72% of his targets (14th) and averaged 10.2 YPT (third). Limited volume (43 targets) allowed him one top-12 fantasy week, but he now has an opportunity to win a job that allowed Ian Thomas 417 pass routes (10th-most among TEs) last season. Arnold is likely still improving and situated well for a potential breakout. The 26-year-old belongs on your sleeper list.

outlooksByWeek.1: Even with Hunter Henry coming off a shoulder injury that sidelined him for most of August, Asiasi is far enough down New England's TE depth chart for fantasy managers to ignore him against Miami in Week 1.

Some wide receivers drafted in the early rounds are thrust directly into action but that won’t be the case for Atwell. With veterans Robert Woods, Cooper Kupp and DeSean Jackson at the top of the Rams receiving depth chart, the 57th overall pick will be brought along slowly. Stash Atwell in dynasty leagues, but don’t expect anything this early in the season.
outlooksByWeek.2: Atwell wasn't asked to make any offensive contributions with the ball in his hands in Week 1 against the Bears. He should not be in starting lineups against the Colts in Week 2.

player.seasonOutlook: Atwell was selected by the Rams in the second round of April's draft. The Louisville product is one of the tiniest players in this year's rookie class at 5-foot-9, 155 pounds. He's a terrific athlete with outstanding game speed, explosiveness, elusiveness and big-play ability, but he isn't going to handle traffic or contested situations very well. Atwell is primarily a slot target (92% over the past three seasons) and figures to be used as a situational screen/gadget and vertical home-run target in the pros. He may have trouble finding his way to consistent snaps and targets in 2021 with Robert Woods, Cooper Kupp, Van Jefferson and DeSean Jackson also in the fold. The second-round investment and Sean McVay's productive offense makes him worthy of a deep league late-round flier.

outlooksByWeek.2: Promoted from Houston's practice squad last Friday, Auclair started in Week 1 against the Jaguars but was not targeted. He should not be in your Week 2 fantasy lineups.

outlooksByWeek.1: Austin could help the Jaguars fill the void left by Travis Etienne's season-ending injury -- with an emphasis on the word "could." Fantasy managers should monitor his role to assess him as a potential waiver-wire pickup,  but he is not a viable play this week.
outlooksByWeek.5: Austin was active for the first time this season and it was rather fortuitous after the Jaguars lost DJ Chark for the season during the opening series of the Week Thursday nigh showcase. Even so, Austin only collected one of three targets for eight yards. Even with the extra time to assimilate into the Jaguars offense, Austin isn’t a fantasy option when Jacksonville hosts the Titans in Week 5.

outlooksByWeek.1: Yet to prove efficient as a rusher in the league, Ballage enters the season competing for backup early-down duties with Benny Snell Jr.
outlooksByWeek.2: Ballage may eventually see the field in third down scenarios, but in Week 1 he watched rookie Najee Harris get all the reps when the offense was on the field. Even if Ballage were to play, he’s a fantasy afterthought.
Barber provides the Raiders with veteran depth while Jalen Richard is out. After not suiting up in Week 1, even if Barber dons the pads for Week 2, his days of being a fantasy factor are history.
outlooksByWeek.4: Barber stepped into the main early-down role with 23 carries in 47 snaps and a career-best 111 rushing yards. It's unclear just how Barber's role will play out once Josh Jacobs is good to go, but he's at least on the radar for this division matchup with a soft Chargers rush defense.

outlooksByWeek.1: All indications are Barkley will be able to suit up for the Giants opener against the Broncos in the Meadowlands. He spent the offseason rehabbing after requiring surgery on his ACL and MCL after last season’s Week 2 injury. However, temper expectations to RB2 status until Barkley demonstrates he’s able to handle his usual high workload.
outlooksByWeek.2: With just 10 carries and one catch (for 27 yards from scrimmage), Barkley's limited role in Week 1 wasn't surprising, given it was his first game back from reconstructive knee surgery. That said, an increased workload seems likely against Washington in Week 2. As such, Barkley remains a viable RB2 with upside.
outlooksByWeek.3: Barkley played on the majority of snaps (84%) against Washington in Week 2 after being limited to just 48% in Week 1. He rushed 13 times for 57 yards (including a 41-yard sprint) against Washington, adding two receptions for 12 additional yards. With a 10-day rest and a favorable matchup against Atlanta in Week 3, Barkley moves back into RB1 territory for fantasy managers.
outlooksByWeek.4: Granted, Barkley missed most of last season, Week 4 marked his first trip into the end zone since the final game of the 2019 campaign. He also gained 51 rushing yards and caught six balls for 43 more, easily being the most productive day so far this season. Barkley's volume renders him a low end RB1, high end RB2 in Week 4's road tilt with New Orleans.
outlooksByWeek.5: Looking back to form, Barkley netted his fourth career game with at least one rushing and one receiving score this past week. Dallas has surrendered 4.7 yards per tote to tailbacks this season, setting up Barkley for another big line in this division showdown.

player.seasonOutlook: Barkley returns to the New York backfield in search of a bounceback campaign following a 2020 season in which a knee injury limited him to 64 snaps. Barkley was the feature back, as expected, out of the gate, handling 15 carries and nine targets while playing 88% of the snaps in Week 1. That aligned with his usage during his first two NFL seasons. Barkley paced all RBs in yardage and fantasy points as a rookie in 2018 and ranked third in yardage and fourth in fantasy points during his 12 full games in 2019. There are suddenly a lot of mouths to feed in New York, but, assuming full health, Barkley is one of the few backs in the league who will push for 25 touches every week. The 24-year-old remains an elite RB1.

Bass was fantasy's No. 4 kicker as a rookie in 2020. The sixth-round pick's career started slowly, as he managed seven or fewer points in his first six games, but he finished strong with a position-best 116 fantasy points after Week 6. He benefited from the Bills' high-scoring offense, as his 59 extra-point attempts were second most and his 34 field goal attempts seventh most among kickers. Bass' field goal accuracy was slightly below average (82.4%), but the 24-year-old will surely be busy again in the same situation in 2021. He's a back-end starting kicker option in most formats.

outlooksByWeek.5: A groin injury has kept Bateman, the team's top pick in the draft, from seeing the field. It's worth stashing Bateman given his impressive prospect profile, but in his debut against a solid pass defense, it's not yet time to start him in fantasy leagues.

player.seasonOutlook: Bateman was selected by Baltimore with the 27th overall pick of April's draft. He has decent size at 6-foot-1, 210 pounds and projects as a perimeter/X receiver in the pros. The Minnesota product is a physical receiver with good route running, speed (reportedly ran a 4.39 40) and post-catch ability. A high-volume target and vertical threat, Bateman handled a prospect-high 43% of his team's air yards in 2020 (albeit in only five games) and a 32% target share over the past three seasons. Volume figures to elude him in Baltimore, however, as the Lamar Jackson-led offense leans heavily on the run and he'll also need to fend off Marquise Brown, Mark Andrews and perhaps Sammy Watkins for targets. Bateman will also open his career on IR, but could return as soon as Week 4. This is not an ideal short-term landing spot, so, along with the injury, Bateman is best left on waivers in season-long leagues.
